<!-- §01 — MANIFESTO (REWRITTEN — FACTUALLY EXPANDED)      -->
<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div id="pane-manifesto" class="tab-pane active">
<section class="section">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="section-head">
      <div class="meta"><span class="num">§01</span> The Manifesto</div>
      <h2>An Open Letter to the Legal Community<br/>and All People of <em>Conscience.</em></h2>
    </div>

    <div class="manifesto-body">

      <div class="doc-status"><span class="dot"></span> Open · Circulating for Co-Signatures · Forensic Edition May 21, 2026</div>

      <p>We write not in anger. We write in clarity — and in precision.</p>

      <p>We write as people who believe in the law — not as it is sometimes practiced, but as it was designed: to protect the innocent, to restrain the powerful, and to ensure that no person is punished for <strong>defending their own life.</strong></p>

      <p>We write because a young man named Karmelo Anthony is about to stand trial in a Texas courtroom for an act that the law of that very state says he had the right to perform. And we write because the public narrative surrounding this case has been contaminated by misattributions, factual errors, and disinformation that must be corrected — not to excuse any act, but because <strong>justice requires accuracy.</strong></p>

      <p>Silence in this moment is not neutrality. <em>It is complicity.</em></p>

      <h3>What Actually Happened — The Verified Record</h3>

      <p>On the morning of <strong>April 2, 2025</strong>, a UIL District 11-5A Championship track meet was underway at <strong>Kuykendall Stadium</strong> in Frisco, Texas. Multiple Frisco Independent School District high schools participated, including Centennial High School and Memorial High School.</p>

      <p><strong>Karmelo Sincere Anthony</strong>, 17, a senior at Centennial High School, was seated in or near the Memorial High School team tent. <strong>Austin Metcalf</strong>, 17, an 11th grader at Memorial High School and a promising athlete, approached and confronted Anthony about his presence in the tent — specifically about seating.</p>

      <p>According to the <strong>official arrest report</strong> obtained by KERA News, and corroborated by multiple witness accounts, the following sequence occurred:</p>

      <p>Anthony told Metcalf: <em>"Touch me and see what happens"</em> — a verbal warning. According to witnesses, Metcalf either grabbed or pushed Anthony. At that point Anthony drew a knife and stabbed Metcalf in the chest. Austin Metcalf died from his injuries. He was found by his identical twin brother, Hunter Metcalf, who held him and tried to stop the bleeding as Austin died in his arms.</p>

      <p>Police arrived and encountered Anthony, who did not flee. When an officer referred to him as "the alleged suspect," Anthony stated unprompted: <em>"I'm not alleged. I did it."</em> He also said, without being questioned: <em>"I was protecting myself"</em> and <em>"He put his hands on me. I told him not to."</em> Anthony then asked if Austin Metcalf was going to be okay. <strong>He cooperated fully and was taken into custody without incident.</strong></p>

      <h3>The Critical Factual Correction — Who Said What</h3>

      <p>Widespread misreporting has confused two separate and critically different statements made by two different fathers. <strong>This distinction matters enormously to the legal and public record.</strong> E5 Enclave corrects it here, on the record:</p>

      <p><strong>Andrew Anthony</strong> — Karmelo's father — gave an exclusive interview to the <em>New York Post</em> on April 3, 2025. He said: <em>"He was not the aggressor. He was not the one who started it."</em> He also described his son as "a good kid" who works two jobs and maintains a 3.7 GPA, and said: <em>"I feel bad for the other parents and family, and words can't explain how both families have been affected by this tragedy."</em> He characterized the stabbing as a heat-of-the-moment act in which his son was provoked.</p>

      <p><strong>Jeff Metcalf</strong> — Austin Metcalf's father, the father of the victim — gave a separate interview on NBC Dallas-Fort Worth and subsequently to Fox News. He described rushing to the stadium, finding his son on a gurney not breathing, and said: <em>"This is murder."</em> He questioned Karmelo's upbringing and parents, but also said: <em>"You know what, I already forgive this person. Already. God takes care of things."</em> Jeff Metcalf was also separately escorted out of the April 17, 2025 press conference organized by Karmelo's family's representatives. He later told the <em>New York Post</em> that he felt "disrespected."</p>

      <p>Jeff Metcalf's twin son, <strong>Hunter Metcalf</strong> — Austin's identical twin brother and an eyewitness — told WFAA: <em>"I tried to whip around as fast as I could. I looked at my brother and I'm not going to talk about the rest. I tried to help him."</em> Hunter Metcalf has been publicly described as a witness to the altercation, and reports indicate he gave a statement to police. Reports also indicate that Hunter's account of what occurred immediately before the stabbing — specifically what Austin did with Karmelo's bag — differed from the accounts of two other eyewitnesses who told police they saw Anthony reaching into his own bag before drawing the knife. <strong>Hunter Metcalf did not give public testimony claiming his brother was not the aggressor.</strong> That statement came from <strong>Andrew Anthony</strong>, Karmelo's father.</p>

      <p>The Frisco Police Department issued a public warning about misinformation circulating online, including a false medical examiner's report. District Attorney Greg Willis also cautioned the public about misinformation. <strong>On this page, we deal only in the documented, sourced record.</strong></p>

      <h3>The Law — Texas Penal Code, Applied</h3>

      <p><strong>Texas Penal Code § 9.31 — Self-Defense:</strong> A person is justified in using force against another when and to the degree the actor reasonably believes the force is immediately necessary to protect the actor against the other's use or attempted use of unlawful force.</p>

      <p><strong>Texas Penal Code § 9.32 — Deadly Force in Defense of Person:</strong> A person is justified in using deadly force against another when they would be justified in using force under § 9.31, and when they reasonably believe that deadly force is immediately necessary to protect themselves against the other's use or attempted use of unlawful deadly force — or to prevent the other's imminent commission of aggravated kidnapping, murder, sexual assault, aggravated sexual assault, robbery, or aggravated robbery.</p>

      <p><strong>Texas has no duty to retreat</strong> for a person who has a right to be present at a location, who is not engaged in criminal activity, and who is not the initial aggressor. This is codified in § 9.32(c).</p>

      <p>The central legal questions in <em>People v. Anthony</em> are therefore:</p>
      <p>1. Was Karmelo Anthony the initial aggressor, or did the physical confrontation begin with Austin Metcalf's grab or push? <br/>
      2. Did Anthony reasonably believe deadly force was immediately necessary to protect himself from the physical contact being applied?<br/>
      3. Was Anthony engaged in criminal activity at the time? (He was not.)<br/>
      4. Did Anthony have a right to be at the location? (He was at a public school track meet.)</p>

      <p>These are the questions a Collin County jury will answer. The prosecution carries the burden of proof beyond a reasonable doubt that Anthony did <em>not</em> act in lawful self-defense. <strong>That is not a low bar.</strong></p>

      <h3>The Case Record — What Is Publicly Established</h3>

      <p><strong>The arrest:</strong> Karmelo Anthony was arrested April 2, 2025 and initially held on a <strong>$1,000,000 bond.</strong> On April 14, 2025, Collin County Judge Emily Miskel reduced his bond to <strong>$250,000.</strong> Anthony was released under strict conditions: ankle monitor, house arrest, permission required to leave home.</p>

      <p><strong>The indictment:</strong> On <strong>June 24, 2025</strong>, a Collin County Grand Jury returned a first-degree murder indictment against Karmelo Sincere Anthony. DA Greg Willis stated in his video announcement: <em>"From this point forward, we'll continue doing our part — fully and fairly — to pursue justice under the law... A defendant is presumed innocent unless and until proven guilty in a court of law."</em></p>

      <p><strong>The gag order:</strong> On <strong>July 28, 2025</strong>, Collin County Judge John Roach Jr. issued a sweeping gag order barring all parties — attorneys, law enforcement, witnesses, expert consultants — from speaking about the case to media or posting about it on social media without prior court approval. Violations are punishable by contempt, fines, or attorney discipline.</p>

      <p><strong>The trial:</strong> Set for <strong>June 1, 2026</strong> in Collin County District Court, McKinney, Texas. Judge John Roach Jr. presides. The trial will include voir dire, opening statements, and a determination of whether Karmelo Anthony's self-defense claim holds under Texas law.</p>

      <p><strong>The potential sentence:</strong> First-degree murder in Texas carries a range of 5 to 99 years, or life, in a Texas state prison, plus an optional fine not to exceed $10,000. Parole eligibility would be after 30 years or half the sentence, whichever is less. DA Willis clarified publicly that Anthony cannot receive the death penalty or life without parole under state and federal law, as he was 17 at the time of the offense.</p>

      <p><strong>Misinformation on record:</strong> The Frisco Police Department publicly warned that a circulating image purporting to be a medical examiner's report was fabricated. The department's statement: <em>"Only official releases from verified accounts should be trusted."</em> KERA News also documented extensive online misinformation and racial disinformation circulating around the case.</p>

      <h3>What We Believe</h3>

      <p>We believe that the right to self-defense is not a right that belongs only to some people.</p>

      <p>We believe that Stand Your Ground is not a selective doctrine — applied when convenient, suspended when the defendant is young and Black and the victim was white.</p>

      <p>We believe that if Austin Metcalf — <em>may he rest in peace and be held in the memory of those who loved him</em> — died as a result of an altercation in which he was the initial aggressor, then the law must be applied honestly and fully. This is not about dishonoring Austin Metcalf. It is about honoring the law.</p>

      <p>We believe that a 3.7 GPA, two jobs, immediate surrender, full cooperation, perfect compliance with every court order for over a year, and a father who spoke publicly with grief and grace — these are not accidents. They are the character of a household that believed in this country. That believed the system would be fair.</p>

      <p>We believe that if the law does not protect Karmelo Anthony — a young man who did everything right after an act he says was forced upon him — then it protects no one. Because the law either means what it says, <em>or it means what the powerful need it to mean in any given moment.</em></p>

      <p><strong>We are calling on the legal community to affirm that belief.</strong></p>

      <h3>What We Ask</h3>

      <p><strong>To civil rights attorneys — particularly those who have committed their practice to the defense of Black life:</strong> Examine this case. Review the arrest report. Study the witness statements. Apply the law as written. A credible, significant self-defense argument exists under Texas §§ 9.31 and 9.32. Make yourselves known to the Anthony family and their defense team before June 1.</p>

      <p><strong>To every attorney who has ever stood in a courthouse and said that Black life has value:</strong> Your voice in this moment carries weight that no press release can match. Add your name below. A young man who did everything right needs the full force of this country's civil rights legal tradition standing beside him.</p>

      <p><strong>To organizations committed to justice:</strong> We are organizing lawful, peaceful court presence support for the week of June 1–5. The courthouse is in McKinney, Texas. Collin County District Court. We are building the infrastructure. Join us.</p>

      <p><strong>To the press:</strong> Cover this case accurately. Attribute statements to the correct people. Andrew Anthony said his son was not the aggressor. Jeff Metcalf said he was devastated and already forgives. Hunter Metcalf described holding his twin brother as he died. These are three different men, three different statements, three different roles in this tragedy. <strong>Report them correctly.</strong></p>

      <h3>Our Credo</h3>

      <p>We believe in the infinite worth of every human life — including Austin Metcalf's and Karmelo Anthony's.</p>
      <p>We believe that the law must be applied equally — not selectively, not politically, not as a weapon against the already vulnerable.</p>
      <p>We believe that a young man who says he defended himself, who surrendered peacefully, asked about his victim's condition, and has complied with every court order for over a year — deserves to walk out of that courtroom free if the law supports it.</p>
      <p>We believe that this moment is a test. Of the law. Of the legal community. Of every organization that has ever said that justice is not just a word.</p>

      <p><em>We are on the right side of that test. We are asking you to be, too.</em></p>

      <p><strong>We stand with truth. We stand with the law. We stand with Karmelo Anthony.</strong></p>
      <p><em>By Grace, perfect ways.</em></p>

