  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="section-head">
      <div class="meta"><span class="num">§02</span> Forensic Record</div>
      <h2>The Case Record — <em>Every Sourced Fact.</em></h2>
    </div>

    <div class="manifesto-body">

      <div class="doc-status"><span class="dot"></span> Forensic Intelligence · Board Standard · All Facts Sourced · May 21, 2026</div>

      <h3>Timeline of Events — Verified Chronology</h3>

      <p><strong>April 2, 2025 — approximately 10:00 AM CDT:</strong> UIL District 11-5A Championship track and field meet at Kuykendall Stadium, Frisco, Texas. Multiple Frisco ISD high schools competing. Heavy rain is falling. Karmelo Anthony (17, Centennial HS) is seated near or in the Memorial HS team tent. Austin Metcalf (17, Memorial HS) approaches and a confrontation occurs over seating/tent space. <em>Source: KERA News arrest report; ABC7; Fox4 News; Frisco PD statement.</em></p>

      <p><strong>10:00–10:15 AM:</strong> According to the arrest report, Anthony issued a verbal warning — <em>"Touch me and see what happens."</em> Witnesses told police Metcalf then grabbed or pushed Anthony. Anthony drew a knife and stabbed Metcalf in the chest. Austin Metcalf collapsed. His identical twin brother, Hunter Metcalf, rushed to him and held him trying to stop the bleeding. <em>Source: KERA News arrest report; ABC7; NY Post.</em></p>

      <p><strong>Immediately after the stabbing:</strong> Anthony did not flee. He walked to police. Unprompted, without being asked any questions, he said: <em>"I was protecting myself."</em> When the officer referred to him as "the alleged suspect," Anthony responded: <em>"I'm not alleged. I did it."</em> As he walked to the squad car, he said: <em>"He put his hands on me. I told him not to."</em> Anthony also asked officers if Metcalf was going to be okay. <em>Source: Official arrest report, KERA News.</em></p>

      <p><strong>April 2, 2025 — later that day:</strong> Austin Metcalf was transported to a local hospital. Despite CPR and blood administration by police and fire personnel, he was pronounced dead. His father, Jeff Metcalf, who had rushed to the stadium after Hunter called him, found Austin on a gurney and accompanied him to the hospital. <em>Source: Jeff Metcalf interview, NBC Dallas-Fort Worth; NY Post.</em></p>

      <p><strong>April 2, 2025:</strong> Karmelo Anthony is booked and charged with first-degree murder. Initial bond set at <strong>$1,000,000</strong>. <em>Source: Frisco PD; Collin County court records.</em></p>

      <p><strong>April 3, 2025:</strong> Andrew Anthony — Karmelo's father — gives exclusive interview to the <em>New York Post.</em> He says: <em>"He was not the aggressor. He was not the one who started it."</em> He describes Karmelo as a good kid with a 3.7 GPA who works two jobs. He expresses sympathy for the Metcalf family. <em>Source: NY Post, April 3, 2025, by Jared Downing.</em></p>

      <p><strong>April 3–4, 2025:</strong> Jeff Metcalf — Austin's father — gives interviews to NBC Dallas-Fort Worth and Fox News. He says: <em>"This is murder."</em> He questions Karmelo's upbringing and parents. He also says: <em>"I already forgive this person. Already. God takes care of things."</em> He describes seeing Austin on a gurney: <em>"I could see all the blood, and I saw where the wound was, and I was very concerned."</em> Hunter Metcalf, Austin's twin brother, tells WFAA: <em>"I tried to whip around as fast as I could. I looked at my brother and I'm not going to talk about the rest. I tried to help him."</em> <em>Source: NY Post; NBC DFW; WFAA; Fox News.</em></p>

      <p><strong>April 14, 2025:</strong> Collin County Judge Emily Miskel reduces Anthony's bond from $1,000,000 to <strong>$250,000.</strong> Bond conditions: ankle monitor, house arrest, permission required before leaving home. <em>Source: Fox4 News; WFAA.</em></p>

      <p><strong>April 17, 2025:</strong> The Anthony family's representatives — the Next Generation Action Network, led by Dominique Alexander — hold a press conference addressing misinformation and death threats. Jeff Metcalf arrives unannounced and is escorted out by police. Karmelo's mother, Kayla Hayes, says her family has received death threats, that her 13-year-old daughter is afraid to sleep in her own bedroom. A fundraiser at GiveSendGo has raised approximately $458,762 for Anthony as of that date. <em>Source: KERA News; People Magazine; Fox4 News.</em></p>

      <p><strong>April–May 2025:</strong> Frisco Police Department warns publicly about a fabricated medical examiner's report circulating online. DA Greg Willis cautions the public about misinformation. KERA News publishes an extensive report on the racial dynamics of the online debate and the disinformation environment. Anthony is reported to have moved to an undisclosed location after death threats. <em>Source: Frisco PD statement; KERA News; Fox4 News.</em></p>

      <p><strong>June 24, 2025:</strong> A Collin County Grand Jury returns a first-degree murder indictment against Karmelo Sincere Anthony. DA Greg Willis announces: <em>"Today, I summarized that evidence, and I asked the Grand Jury to return a first degree murder indictment against Karmelo Anthony — which they did."</em> He also states publicly: <em>"A defendant is presumed innocent unless and until proven guilty in a court of law."</em> <em>Source: Collin County DA press release, collincountyda.com, June 24, 2025.</em></p>

      <p><strong>July 28–29, 2025:</strong> Judge John Roach Jr. issues a sweeping gag order. Attorneys, law enforcement, witnesses, and expert consultants are barred from making public statements or posting on social media about the case without court approval. Violations subject to contempt, fines, or attorney discipline. Trial date is confirmed: <strong>June 1, 2026.</strong> <em>Source: WFAA; KERA News; Dallas Morning News.</em></p>

      <p><strong>May 21, 2026 (present):</strong> Trial is 11 days away. All parties under gag order. Case status: no plea deal has been announced. Pretrial motions and hearings are ongoing under Judge Roach's management. <em>Source: Fox4 News 2026 Texas Court Cases to Watch; Reddit/frisco.</em></p>

      <h3>The Witnesses — Public Statements on Record</h3>

      <p><strong>Eyewitnesses at the scene (unnamed):</strong> Multiple witnesses told police that Anthony warned Metcalf with the words "Touch me and see what happens" before Metcalf grabbed or pushed him. Two witnesses told police they did not realize Anthony had a weapon before he drew it. One witness reported that Metcalf "aggressively grabbed" a bag. Witness accounts about the exact sequence of events — particularly regarding the bag — diverged. <em>Source: KERA News arrest report; WKYC Channel 3.</em></p>

      <p><strong>Hunter Metcalf:</strong> Austin's identical twin brother was present and witnessed the stabbing. He gave a statement to police. His account of the moments immediately before the stabbing — specifically what Austin did or didn't do with a bag — reportedly differed from accounts of two other eyewitnesses. He told WFAA immediately after: <em>"I tried to whip around as fast as I could. I looked at my brother and I'm not going to talk about the rest. I tried to help him."</em> <em>Hunter Metcalf did not make a public statement that Austin was "not the aggressor." That statement was made by Karmelo's father, Andrew Anthony.</em> <em>Source: WFAA; NY Post; WKYC Channel 3 report.</em></p>

      <p><strong>Andrew Anthony (Karmelo's father):</strong> Gave exclusive interview to NY Post, April 3, 2025. Said his son was not the aggressor, was provoked, and was a good kid. Expressed sorrow for both families. <em>Source: NY Post, April 3, 2025.</em></p>

      <p><strong>Jeff Metcalf (Austin's father):</strong> Gave interviews to NBC Dallas-Fort Worth and Fox News. Described the death as murder, questioned Karmelo's upbringing, expressed immediate forgiveness. Arrived at Anthony family press conference on April 17 uninvited. Later told NY Post he felt disrespected. <em>Source: NBC DFW; Fox News; NY Post; KERA News.</em></p>

      <p><strong>Dominique Alexander (Next Generation Action Network):</strong> Said at the April 17 press conference: <em>"He should be afforded the same rights that Kyle Rittenhouse had, Daniel Penny, and all of the people who have claimed whatever their defense was."</em> <em>Source: KERA News.</em></p>

      <h3>Texas Self-Defense Law — Legal Analysis</h3>

      <p><strong>The core legal question this jury must answer:</strong> Was Karmelo Anthony acting in lawful self-defense under Texas Penal Code § 9.32?</p>

      <p><strong>Elements of the self-defense claim:</strong> (1) Anthony was not the initial aggressor — the arrest report reflects he issued a verbal warning before physical contact was made by Metcalf; (2) Metcalf made physical contact first — grabbed or pushed Anthony; (3) Anthony was at a location he had a legal right to be; (4) Anthony was not engaged in criminal activity; (5) Anthony did not retreat — Texas law does not require it; (6) Anthony reasonably believed deadly force was immediately necessary to protect himself.</p>

      <p><strong>The prosecution's counter-argument:</strong> That producing a knife in response to a grab or push constitutes disproportionate force; that Anthony escalated the confrontation verbally ("Touch me and see what happens") in a manner that makes him at least partially responsible as an aggressor; and that reasonable belief in the necessity of deadly force was not established by a grab or push alone.</p>

      <p><strong>The defense's strongest argument:</strong> That under § 9.32(c), a person who did not provoke the use of force against himself and who is not engaged in criminal activity has no duty to retreat. If Metcalf physically initiated contact, Anthony had the legal right to respond with force — and the degree of force he used is the jury's determination of reasonableness, not a bright-line legal rule. Legal experts quoted by WFAA have noted that self-defense is likely to be the central issue at trial and that a credible argument exists. <em>Source: WFAA legal expert analysis; Reddit/TrueUnpopularOpinion; gambonelaw.com.</em></p>

      <p><strong>Potential sentence if convicted:</strong> First-degree murder — 5 to 99 years or life in Texas state prison, plus optional fine up to $10,000. Parole eligibility: 30 years or half the sentence, whichever is less. No death penalty available (Anthony was 17 at time of offense). <em>Source: Collin County DA announcement; Texas Penal Code § 12.32.</em></p>

      <h3>The Racial Dimension — What The Public Record Shows</h3>

      <p>Karmelo Anthony is Black. Austin Metcalf was white. The case immediately became a flashpoint for national racial debate online. Fringe groups used Austin Metcalf's death to promote explicitly white nationalist messaging, which Jeff Metcalf himself publicly condemned — calling out "Protect White Americans" protesters who attempted to claim his son's death: <em>"They don't give a s— about my family."</em> <em>Source: Jeff Metcalf interview reported by Fox4 News.</em></p>

      <p>On the other side, extensive disinformation circulated claiming that Karmelo was an innocent victim of systemic racism with no factual grounding in the documented record. The Frisco Police Department and DA Willis both warned publicly about misinformation from all directions.</p>

      <p>KERA News published an extensive analysis of the racial dynamics of the online debate, documenting how the case became a vessel for competing narratives that frequently departed from the documented facts. <em>Source: KERA News, May 7, 2025.</em></p>

      <p>E5 Enclave's position: The racial dimension of this case is real and cannot be separated from how it has been perceived and prosecuted. A million-dollar initial bond for a teenager with no prior record, in a self-defense case with contested witness accounts, raises questions that must be asked. These questions do not require presuming Anthony's innocence or guilt. They require applying the same standards that this society applies — or claims to apply — in every comparable case.</p>

      <h3>Sources on the Public Record</h3>

      <p>The following sources were used in the preparation of this forensic report. All are publicly available without FOIA request:</p>

      <p>• Official Arrest Report, Frisco PD — obtained by KERA News, April 2025<br/>
      • Collin County DA press release — collincountyda.com, June 24, 2025<br/>
      • WFAA: Gag order report, July 29, 2025 (Rachel Snyder)<br/>
