      <div class="dateline">For Immediate Release · [Date Upon Authorization] · Liberty City, Miami, Florida</div>

      <div class="press-head">E5 Enclave Incorporated Issues Forensic Case Review and Open Call for Legal Solidarity Ahead of June 1 Karmelo Anthony Trial</div>

      <div class="press-subhead">The Miami-based nonprofit has published a comprehensive, sourced forensic record of the People v. Anthony case — correcting public misattributions and calling on the civil rights legal community to examine the self-defense evidence before trial.</div>

      <p><strong>LIBERTY CITY, MIAMI, FLORIDA —</strong> E5 Enclave Incorporated (EIN 99-3822441), a 501(c)(3) nonprofit organization headquartered in Liberty City, Miami, today released a comprehensive forensic case review of <em>People v. Karmelo Sincere Anthony</em>, set for trial June 1, 2026 in Collin County District Court, McKinney, Texas.</p>

      <h3>The Correction</h3>

      <p>The review corrects a widely circulated misattribution that has contaminated public discourse around the case: the statement that the defendant "was not the aggressor" was made by <strong>Andrew Anthony</strong>, Karmelo's father, in an April 3, 2025 interview with the <em>New York Post</em>. It was not made by Austin Metcalf's father, Jeff Metcalf, nor by Austin's twin brother, Hunter Metcalf. Jeff Metcalf has publicly characterized the incident as murder and expressed forgiveness. Hunter Metcalf gave a statement to police and described holding his dying brother to WFAA. These are distinct individuals with distinct roles in the factual record. Accurate attribution matters to the legal record, to both families, and to the public's ability to assess this case fairly.</p>

      <h3>The Legal Call</h3>

      <p>The review examines the self-defense argument under Texas Penal Code §§ 9.31 and 9.32, including Texas's no-duty-to-retreat provision. Based on the publicly documented facts — that Metcalf made physical contact with Anthony after receiving a verbal warning, that Anthony surrendered immediately, that Anthony had no prior criminal record, and that multiple witnesses described Metcalf as the initiator of physical contact — E5 Enclave is calling on civil rights attorneys to examine the case and make themselves known to the Anthony family's legal team before June 1.</p>

      <h3>The Organizational Position</h3>

      <p>"We are not here to dishonor Austin Metcalf or his family," said Israel Lee Armstead, President and Chief Visionary Officer of E5 Enclave. "We are here to insist that the law be applied equally. If the evidence shows that Karmelo Anthony acted in lawful self-defense under the laws of the state of Texas — and the documented record raises serious questions about whether it does — then a jury must decide that freely, without the pressure of disinformation, without the burden of a million-dollar bond, and without the weight of a racially charged public narrative that has substituted outrage for accuracy."</p>

      <p>E5 Enclave's Black Dragons Initiative is organizing peaceful, lawful court-presence support for the week of June 1–5 in McKinney, Texas. Organizations and individuals seeking to participate may contact E5 Enclave at israel@e5enclave.com or via the support form at e5enclave.com/justice/karmelo-anthony.</p>

      <h3>About E5 Enclave Incorporated</h3>
      <p>E5 Enclave Incorporated is a 501(c)(3) nonprofit organization (EIN 99-3822441, UEI H8NGXEYE2HH8) headquartered in Liberty City, Miami, Florida. Founded in 2024, E5 operates three program verticals: the McCartney Academy (youth development), FarmBlock (food sovereignty and community data), and the Black Dragons Initiative (civic engagement and justice advocacy). E5 Enclave is registered in SAM.gov (CAGE: 07E88) and operates as a Microsoft Nonprofit and Google for Nonprofits partner organization.</p>

